hi, how are the fees paid out on a USDC-ETH LP? I see that i am getting about 50:50 of each. But, aren't the fees actually collected in ETH?
and are the fees paid on both deposit and withdrawal?

Fee is paid in the input token. So in this case, if USDC-ETH swap
the fee will be in ETH
USDC is not an input token?

The fees you will be receiving will be based on the token pair that you deposited. If you provided liquidity for token A and token B, fees will be in token A and token B. The fees you get for a specific trade will depend on what the input token / token the trader is selling.
thank you so if USDC is deposited by a trader and ETH withdrawn. Which token is paid to the LP?
The input token, in this case, is USDC.

Thank you! By positions I largely mean assets. That is, a traditional market maker (e.g Jane Street) has a pool of capital from which draws funds to buy and sell, ussuly on a very short term. The market maker makes the money of the spread, and this, of course, is what creates the liquidity in the market. In that, the market maker also takes on risk (e.g what if it buys Apple for $100 but no one is willing to by it for that high a price -- the market maker loses money). How is moonbeam different from other chains?

Moonbeam is an EVM compatible parachain on Polkadot. Moonbeam is built using Rust and the Substrate framework, enabling rich tools for implementation, but also allowing for specialization and optimization. Moonbeam allows users to interact with:
EVM comptible / Polkadot / Dotsama + Cosmos ecosystem chains.

in general, the main goal of Moonbeam is to connect a ton of different chains and become an advanced place to build dapps, that is, developers will be able to build dApps, where, in turn, users will be able to interact with a large number of different assets in one place, that is, the main goal is to create the most convenient product for both developers and users.  

the Moonbeam team is currently working on a new milestone and is a pioneer in the field of so-called connected contracts. one of the use cases is a one-click swap, without having to look for bridges and so on. 

connected contracts refer to the cooperation of smart contracts on the ‚Äúbackend‚Ä?of the DApps users interact with on the blockchain. These contracts are connected across blockchains so there is no need to bridge assets in order to use assets in any application, on any connected chain. Moonbeam based connected contracts can use different messaging transports to send messages to other chains. XCM, Axelar, LayerZero, Hyperlane. once Chainlink CCIP is available i expect it will be available as a messaging transport as well.

Moonbeam founder Derek talked about all the advantages of Moonbeam in his speech at Polkadot Decoded: 
1. https://youtu.be/th3lQ5oucwg
and this is also worth listening to:
2. <https://youtu.be/b4MSjExESB0>

Uniswap is permissionless and decentralized. No one can stop anyone from using it unfortunately.
I only know of opensea, but remember to use caution and know your position is closed before doing anything like that

Uniswap is a censorship resistant system. This means that no one can prevent someone from using it. This includes both the good and the bad kind of censorship. A totalitarian government cannot prevent a token that goes against their interests from being traded on Uniswap, but also no one can prevent scammers from having their scam token traded on Uniswap.

It should be some kind of mechanism to protect against scammers getting away with stolen funds, we can't be living in a world of fantasy. Totalitarian is one thing, allowing scammers to get away time after time is another. Devs behind these swaps are smart enough to figure out a way to filter through the shady stuff. have some kind of control before being able to swap.. a cool of period of some sort and in the mean time if a report comes in against a wallet then you stop it for double checking
Just my opinion, its frustrating to lose 200k in a min to a scammer and not be able to do anything about. also Jaxx Liberty wallet is a scammers dent, why not block list addresses coming from there?

@Cryptx let's say you wanna set an lp.

Coin v coin

So 1 USDC  1 ETH

You value eth at 1 usdc.

Because of this, if someone wants 1 eth, they put in 1 usdc, so you have 2 usdc and 0 eth.

This is an LP.

That line shows a ratio trade. 

Let's say 1000 usdc 100000 eth, this means there is already a ratio, when you add, you add into this ratio and decide where you want to trade between
Using easy numbers to keep it simple. You cover the full spread and it could give you worse returns than a tight spread
If, let's say, you say "I'll only trade" within a small spread of current traded value, you are more likely to get fees, but, you may also suffer impermanent loss because of scam wicks
*scam wick is a term which indicates sharp movement UP or DOWN and has nothing to do with legitimacy of the coin*

Ex. Scam wick positive and negative.

Both these can cause liquidations <for those who leverage> and or impermanent loss. <for lps>

Hello everyone.

My name is Erden Karso and I currently work at Cyber Capital as a researcher. I am writing my master's thesis on whether incentive designs and voting mechanisms within DAOs or traditional/public companies are more efficient and effective at mitigating agency problems.

I am searching for active contributors within DAOs to interview. DAOs are a relatively new concept that needs more (academic) research and I will try my best to make sure that this research adds value to the crypto space and DAOs. The agency problem is a conflict of interest that occurs when agents (e.g. managers) don't fully represent the best interests of principals (e.g. shareholders/owners). In DAOs, the members are both the principal and the agent.

Are some of you interested to help make research literature less outdated? Interviews will be around 30min only. Please let me know.

Thank you for your time.

You mean the Genie.xyz collection?
There are no "gems" in that collection. I asked which NFT the "Genie:Gem NFT" refers to.

"This tier is also available to wallets that purchased a Genie:Genesis NFT or a Genie:Gem NFT between 5:59 pm and 9:15 pm UTC on June 21st."
-- I assume Genie:Gem NFT refers to The Genie's Lamp from the Yat Gems collection.

The time range for eligibility corresponds _exactly_ to these tweets: <https://twitter.com/Uniswap/status/1539306971899351040> <https://twitter.com/Uniswap/status/1539356280212553728>

You can see that the price of the Genie's Lamp NFT (i.e. Genie:Gem NFT) was 0.1 ETH before the news and was likely pumped by misinformation and still selling for 0.3 ETH about a day later. The price did not *return* to pre-misinformation levels until sometime the next day (on OpenSea, specifically). Yet the eligibility requirements between and end strictly when the tweets were made (a 3 hour range). Some Genie:Gem NFT *holders* were also affected by this mishap as they chose to continue holding their Genie:Gem NFT (and chose not to sell into the news immediately). The same could possibly be said about the Genie:Genesis NFTs. [Misinformation included which NFTs were eligible (Genie:Genesis & Genie:Gem) and the snapshot date for holders.]

There are 76+2 Genie:Genesis NFTs. I assume all were included in the snapshot for April 15th.
And there are 69 Genie:Gem NFTs. At least a few were made eligible for the airdrop because they were "bought" during that 3 hour window on Jun 21st. It's a 5 million USDC airdrop; I estimate the airdrop fund would have increased by 1% if every holder had been made eligible. Why couldn't holders of this relatively small collection also have been made eligible (e.g. before the first tweet)? Or the buyers who bought the Genie:Gem NFT slightly after the 3 hour-window (a day later), paying an inflated price? It seems it also took the price of the Genie:Genesis NFT about a day to return to pre-misinformation levels -- not 3 hours. There is one sale of the Genesis collection on OpenSea 20-minutes outside of the eligibility window that I think was clearly inflated by misinformation (as the prices dropped a day later): <https://etherscan.io/tx/0xd1d7d54f709f1b1ec62f8459e1c8f706e745d55c8fb7a98c9c78da1ae0cbb978>

I do not think increasing the 5_000_000 budget by ~50_000 would have been unreasonable, and would have encompassed more parties affected by the misinformation mishap. (I just think a 1% increase is a relatively minor increase for this airdrop.)

I conclude misinformation is what pumped the prices of these NFTs for up to 24 hours, and that the 3-hour eligibility window was not adequately long.
Genie:Gem and Genie:Genesis aren't collection names nor are they the title of the NFTs (as far as I know). It would be helpful to refer to the specific NFTs or collections. __There is NO "Gem" NFT under the Genie.xyz collection__(0xc466e2F98f95CC4Cde31B134906f59E8264c1BE0)

MY Proposal
In support of furthering the vision of Multichain Uniswap, proposing that the Uniswap community vote to authorize the deployment of Uniswap bridge. We hope this proposal will serve as an example to create a generalizable, trust-minimized approach to cross-chain deployments, with the goal of supporting a multichain Uniswap ecosystem.

As implied in the name, bridges allow one to easily migrate tokens from one chain to another. 

For example converting from Ethereum to Arbitrum, Optimism, Polygon, Celo you will need to have some ETH in your Ethereum wallet to cover gas fees when converting. Similarly user should be able to migrate from the different chains supported by Uniswap

For this we would be creating separate tab in the home page of Uniswap.

Example use case
To switch between Ethereum and Arbitrum:
Click on the "Bridge" tab, and select "Arbitrum Bridge":

This will take you to the Arbitrum Token Bridge, where you can connect your wallet and "deposit/withdraw" tokens to and from the Arbitrum network.

Conclusion

@Andy Just to add to what Rey said. If you noticed, there was an Import Pool button on the UI. You need to import first to find your pool then remove liquidity.

Also, when you added liquidity the first time, you received UNI-V2 LP tokens which represents your share of the pool. When you staked your LP tokens, it leaves your wallet and that is why you cannot find your pool while it was staked.
Only after you unstake will you get back your LP tokens in your wallet. You can only remove liquidity if you have the LP tokens back in your wallet.

2. Select the APEFI and ETH tokens.
3. Once found, click on Manage Pool
4. Remove Liquidity.

Hi there, you don't receive liquidity rewards, but LPs earn fees. LPs earn a fee on every trade in the pool, split pro rata across LPs of that pool. You can read more here: https://docs.uniswap.org/concepts/protocol/fees
Fees are paid based on the input token of the trader, so you get a combination of both of the LP you provided.

Not sure which video you're referring to, but when you provide liquidity on Uniswap, you need to choose which fee tier you want to add liquidity to. This is the % you will earn in fees. You will earn fees for your liquidity as long as your position is in range with the pool.

The fees you will be receiving will be based on the token pair that you deposited. If you provided liquidity for token A and token B, fees will be in token A and token B. The fees you get for a specific trade will depend on what the input token / token the trader is selling.

but when there's a known scam and uniswap still hosts the contract, I don't understand how Uni doesn't share some form of culpability

as reported there's a uni LP between CORE and USDT that allows USDT -> CORE transfers but not CORE->USDT transfers.  I'm all for censorship resistance, but if you can't transact both ways in a Uni-LP, seems awfully silly to not do something about that contract.
Can I issue a proposal to change this behaviour?

I think you have discussed this with @Bing¬≤  in detail in your ticket. Anyway, you can ask in #üíª‚îÇdev-chat if it's even possible for the contract to detect ALL ways how scam tokens are coded and if there is a solution, you can do a proposal in https://gov.uniswap.org/ with regards to its implementation

Alternatively, you can check#üê∂‚îÇscam-token-guide  for guidance before participating in activities related to those tokens. Additionally, if you do not wish to conduct your own research as stated when importing the custom tokens, it may be advisable to refrain from engaging with those tokens at all.

Of course, I have culpability as well for not doing enough due diligence or testing swaps in both directions.  But, tbh, I would never have thought there would be a contract on Uni where I couldn't swap in or out.  My previous understanding of scam tokens is that they'll create an LP, find ways to manipulate a pump and then rug the stable coin side of the LP, leaving others with valueless tokens.  I didn't expect a contract on UNI that wouldn't be swappable in a given direction.
You'll be surprised just how many tokens are like this are in the space üò¨ . You can stick with the listed assets for the meantime as you try to learn on how to spot these scams

As for solutions to this, one simple one would be if a contract is found unswappable in both tokens, to at least delist it from the platform and ideally take over the pool.  I guess that introduces other vulnerabilities and "governance" but if the contract verifiably cannot swap in both directions, I cannot think of a case where an honest actor would be harmed if Uni were able to seize the contract.

Not a dev but I really doubt if it would be simple to identify if a token is unswappable since there are mutliple ways to do it so. Feel free to have it discussed in #üíª‚îÇdev-chat for the possibility. Best thing you could do for now is to DYOR and check these tokens individually. #üê∂‚îÇscam-token-guide will help you a lot

if you now rebalance at 0.10 in first case you pay more for the btc to get it back, that you previously sold for eth and vice versa

Ensure that blind signing is enabled in the Ethereum app settings on your Ledger device.

1. Unplug the hardware wallet and then plug it in again.
2. Unplug the hardware wallet, close your browser, open your browser, plug the hardware wallet in.

4. Make sure you don't have any other apps open that are using the hardware wallet.
5. Try a different USB port.
6. Restart your computer.

Anyone can create a pool in Uniswap. When you add liquidity to a pool, the Uniswap protocol creates a pool address/contract for this which anyone can interact with when they add/remove liquidity. However, there are pools wherein a user might not be able to remove liquidity or only whitelisted address can but this is not an issue with the pool contract but with the token itself. Ultimately, it's the token you need to do due diligence on not the pool address/contract. Hi guys, is there some articles about lp v3? When adding liquidity, what is the diffence between the fees you can choose?

If the current price goes out of the range and after that goes in, what happen?
Thanks

You can refer these help articles: https://support.uniswap.org/hc/en-us/categories/8122334631437-Providing-Liquidity- 

The difference between fee tiers is the amount of fees you receive for providing liquidity to a pool. The UI will show you which fee tiers, for the token pair you're providing, most LPs choose.

If price goes out range - you will not earn fees. If prices goes in, you will continue earning fees.

Hi, could anyone explain the role of the LP tokens and time in a pool relate to the fees an lp gets in v2? How do the the lp token minting/burning affect the fees one gets? I‚Äôve heard that fees ‚Äòcompound‚Ä?on v2, but how? Thanks!
The amount of LP tokens you get will represent your pool share on that liquidity and fees are proportional to your pool share

Ok yeah I‚Äôve heard that, but what determines the total amount of lp tokens for a pool at any given time? The core of my ?/concern has to do with say 2 lps, one in a pool for years, one in for a day, but they have the same lp tokens‚Ä?and those lp tokens have a certain current value, they exit, and they get the same fees? Or the one who has been in for years has claim of more fees when they exit?

Are v2 fees really a function of lp entries and exits, and not the amount of volume of trading during the time you were in to the pool, according to the percentage of the pool you owned at the time of each trade?

The total amount of LPs in the pool will increase or decrease over time depending if people are adding or removing LP. As for the 2 LPs in your scenario, if they have the same amount of LP token, they will have the same pool share at a given time regardless if the other has minted at an earlier date. As for the formula itself, best to ask in #üíª‚îÇdev-chat

I‚Äôm guessing that‚Äôs why Uniswap went to v3 because it seems as if someone were to time their lp entries and exits, they are really gaming into taking the capital of the other lps that stay in? Is this why products have farming rewards for lps in v2, so the project and its treasury can sssentially suction the ETH of the lps?
Unless the v2 lp tokens work in a way so that two lps that enter at dif times can never have the same amount of lp tokens
no as the Liquidity they add would have to be more to get the same LP tokens as the one who has been in there longer
Cool, that‚Äôs what I thought, in my scenario, I had in mind that the second person had to put in more capital, but even so, why should they get any fees of the trades for the last years?
e.g. a year before, one added 100 USD to 1 ETH and get X LP tokens, to get the same amount of LP tokens today, you'll need way more than that to match the current LP tokens
They don't, fees get auto compounded as they are received

Ok, so when the first lp exits, even though their LP tokens show a current value, (a certain number of ETH and ABC) when they exit, they also get additional fees that are theirs from the pool, that are not necessarily shown in the current lp token backing?

Try to unlearn on how fees are working. When fees are generated, they are auto-compounded to the pool thus appraising the value of the current LPs. As more add LPs to the pool, new LPers might need more to get the same LP tokens for those who has been in the pool longer

I‚Äôm not sure what you mean? Fees are the only reason to provide liquidity are you saying as I suspected above? That lp‚Äôing fees in v2 are really a function of entries and exits, and not the volume that has taken place while you were in the pool?

Let me go back to your example

Person A provided 1 token X and 2 token Y and got 3 LP token
A year later Person B provided 10 token X and 17 token Y and got 3 LP token

They both have 3 LP token and if they were to withdraw 3 LP token immediately after person B provided LP, they would get the same amount equally being

Person A 10 token X and 17 token Y
Person B 10 token X and 17 token Y

Person B while having the same no. of LP token doesn't necessarily mean he got shares from the previous fees while Person A gains from it from 1 token X to 9 token X and so is the other. These are exaggerated values though but should clarify things

because the approval was only for the specific amount so it protects you in case there are exploits found in the contracts involved in the swap which can drain any amount you have in your wallet for the specific tokens (assuming you did approval for unlimited amounts)

in your case, if you sold 100 Token A, the approvals that you signed allow Uniswap to transfer only 100 Token A on your behalf, nothing more. Assuming you sold 100 Token A, Uniswap can no longer move Token A on your behalf since its allowed to transfer 0 Token A.

in the past, your approvals are mostly for max amounts of allowance to Uniswap (or other DEX), for example, approvals used to be 1000000 Token A. Unless you sold a total 1000000 Token A, you wont need to sign any more approvals until then.

Hi there, my transaction sometimes fail and i lost around $50 in gas, is there any way to solve this ?

There can be multiple reasons for a failed tx.

tips to make sure your tx doesn't fail
use the average or high gas value when making a transaction
make sure your deadline is long enough to cover the time it takes the transaction to be picked up in a block (faster/more gas does speed this up to be accepted sooner)
Make sure your slippage value is enough to cover the changes in price that happen every block there is a trade. Prices jump a lot more during high volume times. You need to have the slippage for that volume to be large enough to cover the price change, but not to much more so as to not be front run

how much is the normal gas fee per buy or sell?

gas fees are the price relative to the work the miners do. The gwei price  multiplied by the amount of data is the transaction cost. So the Gass limit is the amount of work that is being done in the tx (which changes based on the contract). The gas Gwei is the cost for that transactions speed and determines if the miners will accept it. This is based off of network traffic and race conditions to get the tx mined fastest.  better descriptions can be found at ethereum.org

Hello guys..
Can I still use uniswap even though I have an Android phone

Hey, this is a great question. When you use a token on a dapp, you need to approve that token first and in my cases, this is an unlimited approval meaning you don't need to reapprove the token on that dapp again. The problem with this is that dapps can be exploited and your funds can be taken from your wallet. One way to prevent this is to allow access to a certain amount of your tokens which is what custom spending cap does. For example, instead of me granting unlimited access to all of my ETH, I can tell a dapp that it only has access to only 0.5 ETH in my wallet. This article goes more in depth https://support.metamask.io/hc/en-us/articles/6055177143579-How-to-customize-token-approvals-with-a-spending-cap#h_01G3E1JE4CPVP1VH8PFS4FH25P

This is 100% dependent on the current gas price

gas fees are the price relative to the work the miners do. The gwei price  multiplied by the amount of data is the transaction cost. So the Gass limit is the amount of work that is being done in the tx (which changes based on the contract). The gas Gwei is the cost for that transactions speed and determines if the miners will accept it. This is based off of network traffic and race conditions to get the tx mined fastest.  better descriptions can be found at ethereum.org

column4:
Not in the traditional sense, but you could do some interesting liquidity concentrations using leveraged tokens. Especially pairing two leveraged tokens together. As long as they meet the ERC-20 standard, they can be added to a UNI-V3 pool.

I would suggest looking into the following topics:
- Leveraged tokens
- Advanced concentrated liquidity positions
- Rebasing & atomic swapping of V3 positions automatically
- Staggering V3 positions

Also look at the Uniswap SDK. You can do a lot with the UI, but you can really do some wild stuff if you're building a dapp from scratch using Uniswap's SDK. You would likely want to build a custom logic for how your leveraged tokens are moved between your positions.
Also, you can utilize the Aave SDK as well to make your dapp more robust (for example use Gelato or another automation tool to collect fees periodically, lend/borrow, and add to your positions).

You can do a lot with the standard UX, but to really build something that lets you leverage with V3, you'll need to understand and use at least 3-5 SDKs and Libraries.

Let me know if you have any questions, I have some experience building non-traditional V3 strategies and leveraged tokens.

A general questino; how can I easily translate a tick into a price of a position? 
example if the lower -upper range for wsteth-weth is 900-1300 (denominated in ticks)

Tick is dependent on the fee tier. In the 0.05% tier, one tick is 0.05%. Take your current price of the fee tier, divide by the percentage, that gives you the tick in terms of asset price. Then multiply that by your upper and lower price to get the high and low tick price. The difference would be the tick range.

Again, this is pretty well documented in the documentation, much cleaner to read and easier than me typing it second hand, as much as I like to be helpful, someone else wrote it better and put it online for free üòâ

It is not. That is called a limit order and not available on Uniswap. Here's the exchanges and networks they're on that offer limit orders where you can set a higher price for your token and it will execute when the price reaches that.

1inch - Many Chains, pretty much all EVM chains. Signature approval. My first choice as the entire limit order process is gasless, so no cost to you.
CowSwap - Ethereum, Gnosis. Transaction approval. Some tokens require gas for approval.
SushiSwap - Ethereum, Polygon, Fantom, Avalanche. Works the same as 1inch, uses the same contract as 1inch and CowSap
Dexalot - Avalanche
SpiritSwap - Fantom Opera
Matcha.xyz - Ethereum. Aggregator, allows for limit orders from many different DEXs
TraderJoe - Avalanche, Arbitrum. May not have limit order in place yet, but the dev branch of their code repo had it there last time I checked, so add that one to the ltl

You can do a pseudo limit order in Uniswap V3 by setting a range that is in the price you want to sell. The benefit being that you can accrue extra fees and set a wider range. The drawback is that it's prohibitively expensive to mint a V3 NFT and adjust values where as true order-book limit orders are essentially free.

Slippage is extremely simple to calculate. It's the constant Product formula for DEXs: `X * Y = k`

Ex:
X = ATOM in LP, price is $200
Y = USDC in LP, price is $1
Assume the initial breakdown of LP is 5 ATOM and 1000 USDC

X * Y = 5 * 1000 = 5000 = k, where k is the constant that can't be changed.

Alice buys 1 ATOM, liquidity of X drops to 4
To keep k constant:
Y = k / X = 5000 / 4 = 1250

So, to buy 1 ATOM, Alice contributes 1250 - 1000 = 250 USDC into the LP.
Even though the price of ATOM was $200, due to the relative size of the LP the slippage was 25%

You can simplify this mentally for estimation in that slippage is equal to the percentage of tokens in the LP that are being removed, added to the price to ensure k remains constant.

If the same pool is 10x bigger, slippage becomes 2.5%, 100x bigger, 0.25%

In an LP protocol without fee structures, slippage would be the only difference in price. Even though most pools are thousands if not millions of times larger than the example above, the fee structure sets a minimum percentage slippage (the tier).

Every transaction will change the price of a coin. For example let's say there's a $NEW/$WETH LP that has all the liquidity in that single pool on UniSwap. The pool is initialized with a starting price of $ETH per $NEW.
When someone purchases NEW, they add ETH to the pool, resulting in a higher ratio of ETH to NEW, increasing the price of NEW.
When someone sells NEW, they remove NEW from the pool, resulting in a lower ratio of ETH to NEW, decreasing the price of NEW.
For a standard curve this follows the constant product formula to determine how much the ratio, and therefore the price changes.

Hello dear team
I make swap on the goerli to usdc but swap failed also taken  high gas fee

Gas fees are charged by the ether network for the work that the miners do in confirming the transaction. All txs that are accepted by the miners will have a fee even if it fails, or is canceled

gas fees are the price relative to the work the miners do. The gwei price  multiplied by the amount of data is the transaction cost. So the Gass limit is the amount of work that is being done in the tx (which changes based on the contract). The gas Gwei is the cost for that transactions speed and determines if the miners will accept it. This is based off of network traffic and race conditions to get the tx mined fastest.  better descriptions can be found at ethereum.org
https://ethereumprice.org/gas/

Any admin here?  Who can help me?

Gas fees are charged by the ether network for the work that the miners do in confirming the transaction. All txs that are accepted by the miners will have a fee even if it fails, or is canceled

gas fees are the price relative to the work the miners do. The gwei price  multiplied by the amount of data is the transaction cost. So the Gass limit is the amount of work that is being done in the tx (which changes based on the contract). The gas Gwei is the cost for that transactions speed and determines if the miners will accept it. This is based off of network traffic and race conditions to get the tx mined fastest.  better descriptions can be found at ethereum.org
https://ethereumprice.org/gas/
https://etherscan.io/gastracker
So i am unable to back my 27$?
yes this was the gas paid to the miners

If a pool doesn't exist for the pair that you want to swap, the router will do a multihop swap, where it will trade `tokenA -> whatever token necessary -> tokenC.`
where `whatever token necessary` can be multiple hops through multiple pools if necessary. The price is calculated based on all the trades it has to make in between your input token and your desired token.

What it explains is creating a single sided liquidity position, which is just a position that is out of range. If you set the `Min Price` and `Max Price` at 1 tick apart, it will go straight through your position. The only caveat being that if you don't then withdraw your position, you run the risk of a price reversal sending you back to where you started.

So really, there's no way to guarantee that the order won't get reversed unless you pull your lq as soon as you've reached your desired goal.

You need 2 ticks(price points) to be able to spread the liquidity in the curve.
So if you provide in the grid of (4357.2, 4357.2), the liquidity is in that segment of the curve. Once the price goes above 4357.2, your position will be fully in LOTUS. If the price goes bellow 4357.2 it will be in fully eth.

So in your example (lowerTick: 4357.2, upperTick: 4457.2). 
This creates a GRID, of where your liquidity will be allocated.
You cant provide in the same price point.

The spending cap is the allowance given by the Approve method that all ERC20 tokens have. Metamask simply allows you to set the arguments (such as the amount) used when calling the Approve method. Most other wallets also support this.
So for example, if you have 100 RPL. You can say you only want to approve 50 RPL. In case you are hacked, the hacker can only use 50 RPL not all of your RPL
When you swap an ERC-20 that you haven't swapped before, you have to approve it which costs a little bit of gas

LPs can pursue single-sided liquidity allocation above the current spot price if they are provisioning the higher valued token or below the current spot price if they are provisioning the lesser valued token.

Uniswap UI uses it's own gas model, this differs from the one used in wallets. The max subtracts the gas amount from your balance.

This is an estimation, wallets over-estimate gas, so to make the transaction successful reduce the amount you are using by a small amount

```
gas fees are the price relative to the work the miners do. The gwei price  multiplied by the amount of data is the transaction cost. So the Gass limit is the amount of work that is being done in the tx (which changes based on the contract). The gas Gwei is the cost for that transactions speed and determines if the miners will accept it. This is based off of network traffic and race conditions to get the tx mined fastest.  better descriptions can be found at ethereum.org
https://ethereumprice.org/gas/
https://etherscan.io/gastracker
```
